<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-165-320  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 165 320.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  March 27 1989 v23 n13 p74(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The fine art of figuring CASE payback. (Product Spotlight)(computer-aided software engineering) (purchasing)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Santosus, Cathleen.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Determining the payback on computer-aided software engineering(CASE) products, which range in price from $6,000 to $50,000,requires bending basic rules of business math and adding in suchsoft costs as learning time and the cultural change implied inautomation of software development.andP;  Joseph Izzo, president ofInformation Technology Group, believes a company breaks even onits investment if a four-to-one productivity gain is achievedwithin a two- to five-year period.andP;  However, productivity must beevaluated against the entire development cycle and softwaremaintenance must be taken into account.andP;  American ManagementSystems' VP Jerry Grochow states a company must understand thecurrent level of productivity of its software development systembefore attempting to cost-justify CASE.andP;  Most experts agreeresults will not be impressive at first, and productivity will godown before it goes up.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer-aided software engineeringSoftware SelectionProgram Development ToolsAutomationCostProductivity.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>